   (Message) ROOT CAUSE: program.c:11 uses `for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++)`,
   so `crc8()` processes `len + 1` bytes instead of `len` bytes. In `main()` at
   program.c:22-23, `buf` has exactly 7 valid bytes, indexed `buf[0]` through
   `buf[6]`, and `crc8(buf, sizeof(buf))` passes `len == 7`. In the debugger,
   execution reached program.c:12 with `i == len == 7`; `&buf[6]` was the last
   valid byte, while `&buf[7]` was the one-past-the-end address. The statement
   `crc ^= buf[i];` therefore reads `buf[7]`, which is outside the supplied
   buffer and triggers the AddressSanitizer buffer-overflow report.
   
   LOCAL FIX: Change the CRC loop to use an exclusive upper bound so it visits
   only valid indices `0` through `len - 1`. Minimal patch: `diff\n---
   a/program.c\n+++ b/program.c\n@@\n-    for (size_t i = 0; i <= len; i++) {\n+
   for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {\n         crc ^= buf[i];\n         for
   (int b = 0; b < 8; b++) {\n             crc = (crc & 0x80) ? (uint8_t)((crc
   << 1) ^ 0x07) : (uint8_t)(crc << 1);\n`. With this change, when `len` is 7
   the last iteration uses `i == 6`, and the loop terminates before attempting
   to read `buf[7]`.
   
   GLOBAL FIX: Represent byte buffers with an API/invariant that makes the valid
   range explicit and consistently exclusive, for example a small `struct
   byte_span { const uint8_t *data; size_t size; };` whose contract is that
   valid elements are always `[0, size)`, and require helper functions such as
   `crc8_span(struct byte_span input)` to iterate with `i < input.size`. Pair
   that with tests for edge lengths, especially zero-length, one-byte, and
   exact-size buffers under AddressSanitizer, so inclusive-bound mistakes in
   buffer-processing loops are caught immediately.
